	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#E2E2E2"><strong>Overview</strong></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><p>The 2012 Ford Edge is a mid-size crossover SUV that is capable of accommodating up to 5 passengers. This is currently offered in 4 trim levels with three different engines to choose from. Due to the abundance of available options, SUV buyers who would be interested in buying the Edge are given the chances to select the version that best suit their driving needs and budgets.  <br />
<br />
Aside from its impressive appearance both inside and outside, the 2012 Ford Edge is expected to attract more buyers since Ford has offered a more fuel-efficient version that is powered by a 4-cylinder engine equipped with the company's EcoBoost system. Due to these impressive characteristics, the Edge would surely emerge as one of the most sought-about SUV models for this year. <br />
</td> 
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#E2E2E2"><strong>Exterior</strong></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><p>One of the strong points of the 2012 Ford Edge is its exterior design. This is because Ford engineers and designers were very successful in making the Edge more pleasurable to look at and drive. The front end of the SUV provides it with a powerful presence. This image is further enhanced by the vehicle's halogen headlamps that were carefully installed to blend with the Edge's fluid and bold grille in front.<br />
<br />
When viewed on the side, the 2012 Ford Edge looks strong and sophisticated. Thanks to its smoother contours that flow seamlessly from the vehicle's front end towards its rear. The rear portion of the Edge is also attractive. Its well-sculpted headlights and the well-defined lines on the rear fascia provide the Edge with a pleasing personality when viewed from the rear. The optional vista roof installed and offered as an optional feature in some of the models of the 2012 Ford Edge that open up to three times larger than any conventional moon roof provided by other vehicles even made this SUV elegant and unique.<br />
</td> 
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#E2E2E2"><strong>Interior</strong></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><p>Aside from its attractive external looks, the 2012 Ford Edge also takes pride of its interior's revolutionary design. Ford has actually used more upscale materials on the vehicle's cabin and this has made the interior areas look more elegant. The cabin's appearance was further enhanced by the addition of the company's popular MyFord Touch that allows the driver to manage and control the vehicle's entertainment, climate, and navigation systems. Ford engineers have also installed 2 customized 4-inch LCD displays on the vehicle's gauge to allow the driver to easily monitor the vehicle's condition.<br />
<br />
The 2012 Ford Edge also provides spacious and luxurious interiors. This vehicle also offers ample legroom and headroom. The leather trimmed seats makes the ride comfortable and the support that each of these provides makes longer trips on board the Edge more enjoyable. The 2012 Ford Edge offers a very limited cargo space compared to other mid-size SUVs such as the Nissan Murano. With the second row seat in use, the Edge only provides about 32 cubic feet of cargo space. The cargo space could easily swell to 69 cubic feet when the second row seat is folded.<br />
</td> 
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#E2E2E2"><strong>Performance & Handling</strong></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><p>The 2012 Ford Edge is currently offered with three engine options. The first engine used is the newly acquired 2.0-liter EcoBoost turbocharged direct injection 4-cylinder engine. The EcoBoost engine is believed to provide the power of a V-6 engine and the fuel economy of a 4-cylinder engine. This engine is capable of producing 240 horsepower and 270 lb.-ft. of torque. This engine is mated to a 6-speed automatic transmission and offered with a standard front-wheel drive system or an optional all-wheel drive system.<br />
<br />
The second engine used in the 2012 Ford Edge is the 3.5-liter V-6 engine that produces 285 horsepower and 253 lb.-ft. of torque. The engine is mated to a 6-speed automatic transmission and offered with a front-wheel drive or all-wheel drive system. The third engine option is the 3.7-liter V-6 engine that produces 305 horsepower and 280 lb.-ft. of torque. This is also mated to a 6-speed automatic transmission with paddle shifters and offered in front-wheel drive and all-wheel drive models.<br />
<br />
When driven, the 2012 Ford Edge offers a comfortable and very quiet ride. Thanks to its cabin that is full of sound insulation.   The Edge also provides solid and secured handling. This SUV is capable of making quick cornering with lesser body roll. In addition to this, the Ford Edge could be easily parked in tighter areas where some of the larger Fords cannot. Although the Edge's use of a turbocharged engine is considered as a wrong move, most buyers are trying to argue this notion since this engine offers added torque compared to the larger V-6 without consuming a lot of fuel. The V-6 engines used in the Edge provide average power, a feature that is quite common for a mid-size SUV with a higher curb weight.<br />
</td> 
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#E2E2E2"><strong>Fuel Economy</strong></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><p>Ford's use of the turbocharged 4-cyinder EcoBoost engine was very successful in improving the fuel economy of some of the 2012 Ford Edge. The models powered by this engine and uses the front-wheel drive system obtained the EPA-estimated fuel economy ratings of  21 miles in the city and 30 miles per gallon on the highway. <br />
<br />
The Edge trims powered by the 3.5-liter V-6 engines with the front-wheel drive systems obtained the EPA-estimated fuel economy ratings of   19 miles per gallon in the city, 27 miles per gallon on the highway, and 22 miles per gallon combined. These ratings eventually drops to 18 miles per gallon in the city, 25 miles per gallon on the highway and 20 miles per gallon combined when the vehicle is using the all-wheel drive system.<br />
<br />
Finally, the 2012 Ford Edge powered by a 3.7-liter V-6 engine with a front-wheel drive system obtained the ratings of 18 miles per gallon in the city, 25 miles per gallon on the highway, and 20 miles per gallon combined. These estimated fuel-economy ratings drop to 17 miles per gallon in the city, 23 miles per gallon on the highway, and 19 miles per gallon combined when the vehicle uses an all-wheel drive system.<br />
</td> 
	</tr>	
	<tr>
